data.content:
Here are the three breaking changes affecting your code in EF Core 10:

---

## 1. `ExecuteUpdateAsync` — now accepts a regular lambda (not an expression tree)

The `SetPropertyCalls<T>` expression-tree overload is gone. Your manual `Expression.Lambda`/`Expression.Call` code **won't compile**.

**Fix** — replace the entire block with a simple lambda:

```csharp
await context.Blogs.ExecuteUpdateAsync(s =>
{
    s.SetProperty(b => b.Views, 8);
    if (nameChanged)
    {
        s.SetProperty(b => b.Name, "foo");
    }
});
```

No expression trees needed anymore.

---

## 2. Complex type column names are now uniquified / nested paths changed

Two sub-changes:
- **Same-named properties** across complex types (e.g. `ShippingAddress.Street` and `BillingAddress.Street`) now get a numeric suffix to avoid silent column sharing.
- **Nested complex types** use the **full path** in column names (`Payment_BillingAddress_City` instead of `BillingAddress_City`).

**Fix** — if you need to preserve existing column names, configure them explicitly:

```csharp
modelBuilder.Entity<Customer>(b =>
{
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.ShippingAddress, p =>
        p.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("Street"));
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.BillingAddress, p =>
        p.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("Street"));
});

// For nested complex types, pin the old column name:
modelBuilder.Entity<Order>()
    .ComplexProperty(o => o.Payment)
    .ComplexProperty(p => p.BillingAddress)
    .Property(a => a.City)
    .HasColumnName("BillingAddress_City");
```

Or just generate a new migration and update your database to adopt the new names.

---

## 3. `IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger` — new `logCommandText` parameter

All methods (`CommandReaderExecuting`, `CommandReaderExecuted`, etc.) now require an additional `string logCommandText` parameter (contains potentially-redacted SQL for logging).

**Fix:**

```csharp
public class MyLogger : IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger
{
    public InterceptionResult<DbDataReader> CommandReaderExecuting(
        IRelationalConnection connection,
        DbCommand command,
        DbContext context,
        Guid commandId,
        Guid connectionId,
        DateTimeOffset startTime,
        string logCommandText)   // ← new parameter
    {
        // Use logCommandText for logging (redacted SQL)
        // Use command.CommandText for actual execution SQL
    }
}
```

---

**TL;DR:** Remove your expression tree machinery (huge simplification), pin column names or re-migrate for complex types, and add `string logCommandText` to your diagnostics logger methods.
